3tf.title: Fallacies
3tf.clickbait: To call something a fallacy is to assert that you think people shouldn't think like that.
3tf.text: A "fallacy" is a mode of thought that is asserted (by calling it a "fallacy") to lead us easily into error, or to not usefully contribute to the project of distinguishing truth from falsehood.  For example, Argumentum Ad Hitlerum is a 'fallacy' because while Hitler did a number of bad things, he also ate vegetables, so "Hitler did X" is not a reliable means of arguing that nobody should do X.

43k.title: Bulverism
43k.clickbait: Bulverism is when you explain what goes so horribly wrong in people's minds when they believe X, before you've actually explained why X is wrong.  Forbidden on Arbital.

4m0.title: Emphemeral premises
4m0.clickbait: When somebody says X, don't just say, "Oh, not-X because Y" and then forget about Y a day later.  Y is now an important load-bearing assumption in your worldview.  Write Y down somewhere.

4m2.title: Multiple stage fallacy
4m2.clickbait: You can make an arbitrary proposition sound very improbable by observing how it seemingly requires X, Y, and Z.  This didn't work for Nate Silver forecasting the Trump nomination.
